"# Chapter 4 — Untyped Lambda Calculus

Where we build the smallest possible programming language — three forms,
one reduction rule — and discover that it can compute anything a computer
can.

Alonzo Church invented the lambda calculus in the 1930s as a foundation
for mathematics. That plan did not survive — Kleene and Rosser found a
paradox in the strongest version — but a piece of it survived
gloriously. The lambda calculus itself, as a *theory of computation*,
turned out to be equivalent to Turing machines: everything one can
compute, the other can compute. This is the *Church-Turing thesis*, and
it is why the lambda calculus is not a historical curiosity but the
theoretical spine of every functional language ever written.

Scheme *is* essentially the lambda calculus with syntactic sugar and
some primitive operators. When you write `(lambda (x) (+ x 1))` in Scheme
you are writing lambda calculus. What we will build in this chapter is a
tiny lambda-calculus interpreter *inside* Scheme, and by watching it work
we will understand what our host language is doing behind the scenes.

> **the runtime says**
>
> *There are two ways to enter functional programming. One is to learn a
> big language — full Scheme, full ML, full Haskell — and infer the
> underlying model from the language's shape. The other is to learn the
> underlying model first — the lambda calculus, in twenty lines — and
> then watch big languages fall out of it as sugar. This chapter is the
> second way. It is faster and it makes the second half of the book
> possible.*

## The three forms

The lambda calculus has exactly three syntactic categories.

1. **Variable.** A name: `x`, `y`, `f`.
2. **Abstraction.** A function taking one parameter: `(λx. body)`. In
   Scheme syntax: `(lam x body)`.
3. **Application.** Applying one term to another: `(f x)`. In our
   Scheme representation: `(app f x)`.

That is it. No numbers, no booleans, no lists, no if-then-else, no loops,
no assignment. Just names, one-parameter functions, and applications. It
looks pathologically weak. It is not.

```scheme
;; A term is one of:
;;   symbol             ; variable
;;   (lam symbol term)  ; abstraction
;;   (app term term)    ; application

;; The identity function:
;;   (lam x x)
;;
;; A constant function returning y:
;;   (lam x y)
;;
;; A function taking two arguments (curried):
;;   (lam x (lam y x))
;;
;; Applying a function to itself (yes, allowed):
;;   (app (lam x (app x x)) (lam x (app x x)))
```

The last one — self-application — is the hairy one. In the untyped lambda
calculus it is perfectly legal syntactically, and as we will see it lets
us encode recursion and, unfortunately, also lets us encode divergent
computations that run forever.

## Beta reduction: the one rule

There is exactly one computation rule in the pure lambda calculus. It is
called *beta reduction*. When you see an application whose function part
is an abstraction, you may replace the whole application with the body of
the abstraction, substituting the argument for the parameter.

    (app (lam x body) arg)  →  body[x := arg]

That is called a *beta redex* (reducible expression) and its result is
its *beta reduct*.

```scheme
;; capture-avoiding substitution: substitute `arg` for free `x` in `body`
(define (subst body x arg)
  (cond
    ((symbol? body)
     (if (eq? body x) arg body))
    ((eq? (car body) 'lam)
     (let ((param (cadr body))
           (inner (caddr body)))
       (cond
         ((eq? param x)                             ; shadowed; leave alone
          body)
         ((member param (free-vars arg))            ; would capture; rename
          (let* ((fresh (fresh-name param
                                    (append (free-vars inner)
                                            (free-vars arg))))
                 (renamed (subst inner param fresh)))
            (list 'lam fresh (subst renamed x arg))))
         (else
          (list 'lam param (subst inner x arg))))))
    ((eq? (car body) 'app)
     (list 'app (subst (cadr body)  x arg)
                (subst (caddr body) x arg)))))

(define (free-vars term)
  (cond
    ((symbol? term) (list term))
    ((eq? (car term) 'lam)
     (filter (lambda (v) (not (eq? v (cadr term))))
             (free-vars (caddr term))))
    ((eq? (car term) 'app)
     (dedupe (append (free-vars (cadr term))
                     (free-vars (caddr term)))))))

(define (fresh-name base used)
  (let loop ((n 0))
    (let ((candidate (string->symbol
                       (string-append (symbol->string base)
                                      \"_\" (number->string n)))))
      (if (member candidate used)
          (loop (+ n 1))
          candidate))))
```

This is the same capture-avoiding substitution we saw in chapter 2, now
applied to lambda terms. The reason it matters here is the same: without
alpha-renaming, `(lam x (lam y x))` applied to `y` would collapse into
`(lam y y)` — the identity function — rather than the constant function
returning the *outer* y that the programmer meant. Alpha-conversion is
what keeps `(lam y x)` faithful to *this particular y* even after
substitution moves in a fresh y.

## Reduction strategies

`subst` is the machinery. Now we need to *drive* it. Given a term with
possibly many redexes, which one do we reduce first? This is called a
*reduction strategy* and the two most important are:

- **Call-by-value (applicative order, eager evaluation).** Reduce the
  argument to a value first, then substitute.
- **Call-by-name (normal order, lazy evaluation).** Substitute the
  argument in unreduced, then reduce afterward.

Scheme uses call-by-value. Haskell uses call-by-name (well, call-by-need,
which is call-by-name plus memoisation). Both compute the same *terminating*
values. They can differ on non-terminating computations: call-by-name
sometimes terminates where call-by-value diverges, but never the reverse
(this is a corollary of the *standardisation theorem*).

Let us write call-by-value first.

```scheme
(define (value? t)
  ;; A value is a lambda abstraction (or, if we had them, a numeral).
  (and (pair? t) (eq? (car t) 'lam)))

(define (reduce-cbv term)
  ;; One step of call-by-value reduction, or 'stuck if no redex reducible.
  (cond
    ((symbol? term) 'stuck)                          ; free variable
    ((eq? (car term) 'lam) 'stuck)                   ; value; nothing to do
    ((eq? (car term) 'app)
     (let ((fn  (cadr term))
           (arg (caddr term)))
       (cond
         ;; reduce the function to a value first
         ((not (value? fn))
          (let ((fn-step (reduce-cbv fn)))
            (if (eq? fn-step 'stuck)
                'stuck
                (list 'app fn-step arg))))
         ;; then reduce the argument
         ((not (value? arg))
          (let ((arg-step (reduce-cbv arg)))
            (if (eq? arg-step 'stuck)
                'stuck
                (list 'app fn arg-step))))
         ;; both are values; do the beta step
         (else
          (subst (caddr fn) (cadr fn) arg)))))))

(define (run-cbv term)
  (let loop ((t term))
    (let ((next (reduce-cbv t)))
      (if (eq? next 'stuck) t (loop next)))))
```

Two clauses: first reduce the function, then reduce the argument, then
perform the beta step. `run-cbv` keeps going until no more reductions
are possible.

```scheme
;; identity applied to identity:
(run-cbv '(app (lam x x) (lam y y)))
;; => (lam y y)

;; a longer chain: ((λf. (λx. (f x))) (λy. y)) z  should reduce to z.
(run-cbv '(app (app (lam f (lam x (app f x)))
                    (lam y y))
               z))
;; => z
```

Notice the second example got stuck at `z` — a free variable — because
we cannot reduce further. In a real language `z` would be looked up in
the environment; here we simply say the term is in normal form.

## Church encodings — computing without built-ins

The lambda calculus has no built-in numbers. Church discovered you can
*encode* numbers as lambda terms.

    0 = (λf. λx. x)
    1 = (λf. λx. (f x))
    2 = (λf. λx. (f (f x)))
    3 = (λf. λx. (f (f (f x))))

The *Church numeral n* is the function that, given `f` and `x`, applies
`f` to `x` exactly `n` times. Arithmetic follows.

    succ = (λn. λf. λx. (f (n f x)))
    add  = (λm. λn. λf. λx. (m f (n f x)))
    mul  = (λm. λn. λf. (m (n f)))

```scheme
(define zero  '(lam f (lam x x)))
(define one   '(lam f (lam x (app f x))))
(define two   '(lam f (lam x (app f (app f x)))))

(define succ  '(lam n (lam f (lam x (app f (app (app n f) x))))))
(define add   '(lam m (lam n (lam f (lam x (app (app m f) (app (app n f) x)))))))

;; (succ zero) should reduce to a term equivalent to one
(run-cbv (list 'app succ zero))
;; => (lam f (lam x (app f (app (app (lam f (lam x x)) f) x))))
;; which further reduces to (lam f (lam x (app f x))) — i.e., one.
```

The reduction is not always in the most compact form — that requires
what is called *eta-conversion* — but the term computed is equivalent
in every functional way to what we expect.

Booleans are also encoded.

    true  = (λt. λf. t)
    false = (λt. λf. f)
    if    = (λb. λt. λf. (b t f))

```scheme
(define true-t   '(lam t (lam f t)))
(define false-t  '(lam t (lam f f)))
(define if-t     '(lam b (lam t (lam f (app (app b t) f)))))
```

A boolean is a function that selects between two things. That is
essentially what `if` does anyway, so encoding it as a two-argument
selector loses nothing. Pairs, lists, trees — every data structure of
functional programming has a Church encoding. Barendregt chapter 6 is a
full catalogue.

## The Y combinator: recursion without recursion

Here is a puzzle. The lambda calculus has no `define`. There is no way
to name a term and reference the name inside itself. So how do we write
a recursive function like factorial? *Every* function you write in the
pure lambda calculus must be anonymous.

The answer is a beautiful trick called the *fixed-point combinator*, or
Y combinator.

    Y = (λf. (λx. (f (x x))) (λx. (f (x x))))

For any function `F`, the term `(Y F)` reduces to `(F (Y F))`, which means
`(Y F)` is a *fixed point* of `F` — a value equal to `F` applied to
itself. This is exactly what you need for recursion.

```scheme
(define Y '(lam f
             (app (lam x (app f (app x x)))
                  (lam x (app f (app x x))))))

;; Factorial. We assume Church numerals and multiplication defined.
;; fact = Y (λg. λn. (if (iszero n) 1 (mul n (g (pred n)))))
```

In our call-by-value interpreter this actually diverges — because `(x x)`
tries to reduce eagerly. The lazy (call-by-name) interpreter handles it.
Or one can use a *call-by-value* variant of Y known as the *Z combinator*:

    Z = (λf. (λx. (f (λv. (x x v)))) (λx. (f (λv. (x x v)))))

The extra `(λv. ...)` wrapping delays the recursive call so it does not
fire until the argument arrives. This is one of the most common tricks
in constructing recursion in strict languages.

The important fact is: recursion is *not primitive* in the lambda
calculus. It is derivable from three forms and one reduction rule. That
was Church's most surprising discovery.

## Church-Turing: what the lambda calculus can compute

We can now sketch what should feel like an astonishing result. *Every*
computable function on natural numbers is expressible as a lambda term.
Not most, not many — *every*.

The proof involves showing that:

1. Every primitive-recursive function (successor, addition, multiplication,
   ...) is lambda-definable. This is straightforward Church-numeral
   arithmetic.
2. General recursion — including functions that might not terminate — is
   captured by the Y combinator.
3. Boolean logic and conditionals are captured by Church booleans.
4. Data structures (pairs, lists, trees) are captured by Church
   encodings.

Turing did the parallel result for Turing machines. Church and Turing
proved the two systems compute the same functions. Kleene had a third
formalism (mu-recursive functions) that also computed the same functions.
Three independent formalisations all landed on the same class of
functions. That is why we believe the *Church-Turing thesis*: what is
intuitively computable coincides with what these formal systems capture.
It is a thesis, not a theorem, because *intuitively computable* is not
a formal notion — but it has resisted every attempt at counterexample
for ninety years.

## The problem the untyped calculus has

The untyped lambda calculus is too permissive. It allows:

    Ω = (λx. (x x)) (λx. (x x))

Watch this term reduce. One beta step gives us `((λx. (x x)) (λx. (x x)))`
— exactly what we started with. Ω reduces to itself, forever. It has
*no normal form*.

That is not, in itself, a fatal problem — a general-purpose language
should allow non-termination, otherwise recursion is fake. But
consider what Ω *means* if we try to interpret lambda terms as
mathematical objects. The term Ω is a well-formed lambda expression that
denotes no value. It has no *meaning* in the semantic sense.

In the 1970s Dana Scott showed how to give the lambda calculus a
semantics anyway — the Scott domain, ordered by information content, in
which Ω denotes the *bottom* element (⊥) that carries no information at
all. This *domain-theoretic semantics* is the way modern language theory
usually reads the lambda calculus. But it is delicate machinery.

A different response — and the one we will explore in the next few
chapters — is to *restrict* the lambda calculus so that Ω is not even
syntactically expressible. This is what *typed* lambda calculi do. In
the simply-typed lambda calculus (chapter 5), every well-typed term
terminates. Full stop, no exceptions. The Y combinator is not typeable;
Ω is not typeable; every well-typed term has a normal form and reaches it
in finite time. That gain — *termination* — is what typing buys you.
The loss is that you cannot write arbitrary programs — general recursion
is gone. You have to add it back with special features, and how you add
it back is the story of a lot of twentieth-century language design.

## Alpha, beta, eta — the three equivalences

Two lambda terms may look different but be *the same function*. The
lambda calculus recognises three equivalences.

- **Alpha equivalence.** Renaming bound variables. `(lam x x)` and
  `(lam y y)` are alpha-equivalent — they are the identity function
  either way.
- **Beta equivalence.** Reduction. `(app (lam x x) t)` is beta-equivalent
  to `t`.
- **Eta equivalence.** `(lam x (app f x))` is eta-equivalent to `f`,
  when `x` does not appear free in `f`. This is the *extensional*
  equivalence: two functions are the same if they behave the same on all
  inputs.

Eta equivalence is not universally adopted. Some presentations use it
(most classical lambda-calculus texts do); some do not (Scheme's `equal?`
does not identify eta-equivalent procedures, because Scheme thinks of a
function as its code, not its extension). We will use it sparingly.

## Variations to try

Implement call-by-name and compare. Take the term
`(app (lam x y) (Y-loop))` where `Y-loop` is a divergent term. Call-by-
value hangs; call-by-name returns `y` in one step. This is a small but
striking demonstration of why lazy evaluation matters.

Add a *pretty-printer* that reprints lambda terms in Church's original
notation — `(λx. body)` with the Greek letter and the period. It makes
your interpreter's output far more readable.

Extend the language with numeric literals and primitive `+` / `*` /
`iszero`. Rewrite factorial without Church numerals. Compare the number
of reduction steps. Church numerals are elegant and slow; a numeric
literal is ugly and fast. That is the pattern of every practical
language decision.

## Try this

Reduce, by hand, the term `(add 2 3)` where `add`, `2`, and `3` are
their Church encodings. Track every beta step. You will find it takes
about a dozen steps and produces a term that, after eta-reduction,
equals `5`. Then feed the same computation to your interpreter and
watch it match, step for step. This is the moment the abstraction
becomes real.

## Closing

We built the lambda calculus. Three forms, one reduction rule, and out
of that we got numbers, booleans, pairs, recursion, and the full sweep
of computable functions. Nothing else in the history of computing has
achieved so much from so little.

Its untyped variant has one flaw: it admits terms with no normal form,
and — related but distinct — it admits terms of no clear meaning. The
next three chapters explore *typing* as a discipline that eliminates
these problems, at the cost of some expressive power we must add back
carefully.

Chapter 5: simply-typed lambda calculus. Terms wear their types on their
sleeves. Ω becomes unwriteable. Every well-typed program halts. And a
door opens to the Curry-Howard correspondence, which will occupy
chapters 7 and 8.
"
